\begin_layout Title

\series bold
Lecture 2: Limited Enforcement and Investment
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These notes the model of Nobuhiro Kiyotaki, John Moore, and Wei Cui (2021).
 That model studies the role of limited enforcement and exogenous shocks
 to the liquidity of assets that serve as collateral or can be sold.
 A second asset, money, has the property of being fully collateralizeable.
 I simplify the model to abstract from the labor supply decisions.
 The goal is to obtain a money demand equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\series bold
Environment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The economy is again in continuous time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Agents have CRRA preferences over consumption goods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The only input for production is capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The key friction is that agents can create capital, only sporadically, when
 a random opportunity emerges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In addition, they face a limited enforcement constraint, to be detailed
 below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\series bold
Environment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All households have the following utility function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(c_{t}\right)=\frac{c_{t}^{1-1/\theta}}{1-1/\theta}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the wealth of each household is composed of its individual capital 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 and real balances of money assets 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}m_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
here 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the price level
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Capital has a price 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}^{a}$
\end_inset

 the return per-unit-of capital, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 the net depreciation of capital.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, capital produces 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{a}$
\end_inset

 units of good per instant of time.
 Think of this rate as the physical return on capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households can either buy capital or invest directly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
to invest directly, households must have an investment opportunity, which
 occurs with Poisson intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
wealth is stored is the sum of capital and monetary holdings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient at this state to specify the budget constraint first in
 discrete time, using the delta notation, intervals of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, to find the continuous-time limit:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{t+\Delta}k_{t+\Delta}+\xi_{t+\Delta}m_{t+\Delta}=\underbrace{\Delta\cdot r^{a}k_{t}-\delta q_{t+\Delta}k_{t}+q_{t+\Delta}\left(1-\Delta\delta\right)k_{t}}_{\text{Capital Earnings}}+\underbrace{\xi_{t+\Delta}m_{t}}_{\text{Revaluation of Monney}}-\Delta\cdot c_{t}.
\]

\end_inset

This equation is also the evolution of wealth.
 Define total wealth as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t}\equiv q_{t}k_{t}+\xi_{t}m_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the continuous time limit of this process you will obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{W}_{t}=\underbrace{r_{t}^{k}q_{t}k_{t}+r_{t}^{m}\xi_{t}m_{t}}_{\text{wealth return (gross)}}-c_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where the rates of return are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{t}^{k}=\frac{r^{a}-\delta q_{t}+\dot{q_{t}}}{q_{t}},\quad r_{t}^{m}=\frac{\dot{\xi}_{t}}{\xi_{t}}\equiv-\pi_{t}.\label{eq:returns}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Notice the distinction between the return on capital and its output.
 The return on capital includes depreciation converting into net terms,
 but there is also a term associated with the capital gains.
 In terms of portfolio weights, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{W}_{t}=\left(r_{t}^{k}\omega^{k}+r_{t}^{m}\omega^{m}\right)W_{t}-\bar{c}_{t}W_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{m}=\xi_{t}m_{t}/W_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{k}=q_{t}k_{t}/W_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the consumption ratio.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{exercise}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Derive the law of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{W}_{t}$
\end_inset

 filling in the missing steps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{exercise}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evolution of wealth follows this path, along continuous paths.
 This budget constraint would hold always in a model without investment.
 Here, some agents will be able to increase their capital stock according
 to Poisson events that arrive with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that their capital will jump according to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t}^{'}=\underbrace{i_{t}-i_{t}^{s}}_{\text{kept investment}}+\underbrace{\left(1-\phi\right)k_{t}}_{\text{kept capital}}\rightarrow k_{t}^{'}=k_{t}+J_{t}^{k}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{t}^{'}=0.
\]

\end_inset

leading to a process of wealth accumulation with jumps.
 Namely, we will obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dW_{t}=\dot{W}_{t}=\left(r_{t}^{k}\omega^{k}+r_{t}^{m}\omega^{m}\right)W_{t}-\bar{c}_{t}W_{t}+\lambda\left[q_{t}J_{t}^{k}-\xi_{t}m_{t}\right]dN_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Technology to Invest and Limited Enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Investment requires goods to create units of capital.
 The technology is such that we require 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(i_{t},k_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 goods to increase capital by 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 represents an adjustment cost of capital, a function that is homogeneous
 of degree one in both arguments.
 It is inessential for the theory, but interesting to contrast it with model's
 where Tobin's Q plays a role.
 The entrepreneur can invest on behalf of the rest of the population.
 Note that when the an agent produces capital, it requires consumption goods
 it does not have because consumption is a flow—there would not be a way
 to have his capital stock jump: There is a hidden timing aspect that is
 not spelled out in the typical business cycle model without frictions.
 Consumption goods are an intermediate input.
 To introduce limited enforcement in a tractable way, assume that capital
 to invest is obtained by selling 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}k_{t}$
\end_inset

 fraction of the capital.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A loan contract is a promise to deliver 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{s}$
\end_inset

 capital goods in exchange for consumption goods that are used for investment.
 This loan is subject to limited enforcement: In particular, the firm has
 
\shape italic
a technology 
\shape default
to divert funds
\shape italic
.
 
\shape default
In particular it can run away with a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\theta_{t\text{ }}$
\end_inset

of the production of 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 capital goods.
 This possibility imposes some constraints on the contracts that can be
 signed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two equivalent arrangements.
 In the one arrangement the firm can use a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

 of the capital stock as collateral.
 In the other arrangement, the firm sells the capital immediately against
 consumption goods.
 Let's show that both environments are isomorphic from the standpoint of
 the firm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Financial Contracts - Capital as Collateral.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the firm pledges the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

 as collateral, it essentially sells claims in amount 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{s}$
\end_inset

 against its future output (in terms of capital).
 If the price of capital is 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t}$
\end_inset

, the firm obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t}i^{s}$
\end_inset

 in consumption goods it can use to finance the production costs.
 If the firm runs away with the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t}$
\end_inset

 of its output, then the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

 of the current capital is lost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{problem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capital producing firm solves the following problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}^{K}\left(k_{t}\right)=\max_{i,i^{s}}i_{t}-i_{t}^{s}
\]

\end_inset

subject to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{t}i^{s}=\varphi\left(i_{t},k_{t}\right)\tag{ (Resource Constraint)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i_{t}-i_{t}^{s}+\phi_{t}k_{t}+\frac{\xi_{t}m_{t}}{q_{t}}\geq\left(1-\theta_{t}\right)i_{t}.\tag{ (Incentive Compatibility)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{problem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first constraint states that promises are sold at the market price for
 capital and that generates some amount of investment goods.
 The sold shares of capital 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}^{s}$
\end_inset

 are multiplied by the price because the lender should be indifferent between
 buying second hand capital and new capital.
 The second is the incentive compatibility constraint induced by limited
 liability.
 It states that the contract must be such that the firm is better-off staying
 in the contract than running away.
 The right-hand side is what the borrower gets to keep if he stays in the
 contract.
 That's the difference between total investment minus his promise, plus
 the fraction of collateral that can be pledged.
 No lender would lend out to if will not receive any proceeds from the investmen
t.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second constraint is written in terms of capital whereas the resource
 constraint in terms of goods.
 We can think of this contracting problem as stemming from an optimal contract
 where all the bargaining power is at the hands of the consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we get rid of sold shares of capital 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{s},$
\end_inset

 the problem translates into:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{problem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The optimal investment is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}^{K}\left(k\right)=\max_{i}i-\frac{\varphi\left(i_{t},k_{t}\right)}{q_{t}}
\]

\end_inset

subject to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{t}\theta+\phi_{t}k_{t}+\frac{\xi_{t}m_{t}}{q_{t}}\geq\frac{\varphi\left(i,k\right)}{q_{t}}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{problem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we solve this problem, we show what happens when the firm sells part
 of the old capital stock in advance instead of pledging capital as collateral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\series bold
Financial Contracts - Capital Sales.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the firm sells the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

 of its capital stock to obtain consumption goods for its investment projects,
 it relaxes the financial constraints imposed by limited enforcement.
 Assume thus that the firm sells that fraction at price 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Together with those sales, it also sells claims in amount 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{s}$
\end_inset

 against its future output.
 The firm obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t}\left(i^{s}+\phi_{t}\lambda k_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 in consumption goods it can use to finance the production costs.
 Again, if the firm runs away with the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t\text{ }}$
\end_inset

 of its output, then the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

 of the current capital is lost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using capital sales, the capital producing firm solves the following problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}^{i}\left(k_{t}\right)=\max_{i,i^{s}}i-i^{s}-\phi_{t}\lambda k_{t}
\]

\end_inset

subject to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{t}\left(i^{s}+\phi_{t}\lambda k_{t}\right)=\varphi\left(i,k\right)
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i-i^{s}\geq\left(1-\theta_{t}\right)i.
\]

\end_inset

Note that in this case, the objective has changed to incorporate the fact
 that when the firm sells capital, it loses the fraction sold from its capital
 stock.
 However, the enforcement constraint has changed because there is no capital
 left-over as collateral.
 Again, I can get rid of 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{s}$
\end_inset

 by using the resource constraint of the firm.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{s}$
\end_inset

 out of the objective one obtains: 
\begin_inset Formula $i-\varphi\left(i,k\right)/q_{t}$
\end_inset

 as the objective.
 Replacing the same object into the incentive constraint, one obtains: 
\begin_inset Formula $i\theta+\phi_{t}k\geq\frac{\varphi\left(i,k\right)}{q_{t}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

