\begin_layout Paragraph*
The linear case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Naturally, in the special case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(i,k\right)=i$
\end_inset

, we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota=\begin{cases}
\iota^{cons} & \text{ if }q_{t}>1\\
\left[0,\iota^{cons}\right] & \text{ if }q_{t}=1\\
0 & \text{ if }q_{t}<1.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

That is, the constraint will always be binding.
 Moreover, in the linear capital cost case, we obtain that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1/q_{t}-\theta}d_{t}=\iota,
\]

\end_inset

or in terms of primitives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota=\frac{q_{t}}{1-\theta q_{t}}\frac{1}{q_{t}}\left(\phi_{t}\omega^{k}+\omega^{m}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Plugging in this amount in the objective we obtain that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{t}^{i}=\left[\frac{q_{t}-1}{q_{t}}\right]\frac{q_{t}}{1-\theta q_{t}}=\left[\frac{q_{t}-1}{1-\theta q_{t}}\right].\label{eq:leverage.multiplier}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Recall that we worked out the case with pledgeable wealth—if we work with
 sales, the return is higher, but we have to account for the reduction in
 wealth do to the sale.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the constract, note that the fraction of sold capital is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i_{t}^{s}=\iota\theta_{t}=\frac{\theta_{t}}{1-\theta q_{t}}\left(\phi_{t}\omega^{k}+\omega^{m}\right).\label{eq:sold.cap}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\series bold
Jump in Wealth after an investment Opportunity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon an investment opportunity, the entrepreneur can sell part of its wealth,
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t}d_{t}$
\end_inset

 and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t}R_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 its wealth going forward.
 Thus, upon any investment opportunity, his wealth jumps accordingly to
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}^{i}\left(\phi_{t}\omega^{k}+\omega^{m}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and the collateral is returned.
 We can also express this us a jump in wealth:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t}^{'}=\left[R_{t}^{i}\left(\phi_{t}\omega^{k}+\omega^{m}\right)+\omega^{k}+\omega^{m}\right]W_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
HJB equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The HJB equation for the entrepreneur is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(W,t\right)=\max_{\left\{ \bar{c},\omega^{k}\right\} }U\left(\bar{c}W\right)+V_{w}\left(\left(r_{t}^{k}\omega^{k}+r_{t}^{m}\left(1-\omega^{k}\right)\right)-\bar{c}\right)W+\lambda\left[V\left(W'\right)-V\left(W\right)\right]+\dot{V},
\]

\end_inset

where I used:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{t}^{k}+\omega_{t}^{m}=1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Guess and verify:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(W,t\right)=\frac{\bar{v}\left(t\right)^{1-\gamma}W^{1-\gamma}-1/\rho}{1-\gamma}
\]

\end_inset

For that we use:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\frac{\bar{v}\left(t\right)^{1-\gamma}W^{1-\gamma}-1/\rho}{1-\gamma}=\max_{\left\{ \bar{c},\omega^{k}\right\} }U\left(\bar{c}\right)+V_{w}\left(\left(r_{t}^{k}\omega^{k}+r_{t}^{m}\left(1-\omega^{k}\right)\right)-\bar{c}\right)W_{t}+\lambda\left[V\left(\left[R_{t}^{i}\left(1-(1-\phi_{t})\omega^{k}\right)+1\right]W\right)-V\left(W\right)\right]+\dot{V}
\]

\end_inset

The intercept is verified.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{w}=\bar{v}^{1-\gamma}W^{-\gamma}$
\end_inset

, then all the terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{1-\gamma}$
\end_inset

 vanish.
 Hence, we verify that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\frac{\bar{v}^{1-\gamma}-1/\rho}{1-\gamma}=\max_{\left\{ \bar{c},\omega^{k}\right\} }U\left(\bar{c}\right)+\frac{\bar{v}^{1-\gamma}}{1-\gamma}\left(\left(r_{t}^{k}\omega^{k}+r_{t}^{m}\left(1-\omega^{k}\right)\right)-\bar{c}\right)+\lambda\left[\frac{\bar{v}^{1-\gamma}}{1-\gamma}\left(\left[\left[R_{t}^{i}\left(1-(1-\phi_{t})\omega^{k}\right)+1\right]W\right]\right)^{1-\gamma}-\frac{\bar{v}^{1-\gamma}}{1-\gamma}\right]+\left(1-\gamma\right)\left(\bar{v}\right)^{1-\gamma}\frac{\dot{\bar{v}}}{\bar{v}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-order conditions requires:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U'\left(\bar{c}_{t}\right)=\frac{\bar{v}^{1-\gamma}}{1-\gamma}.
\]

\end_inset

After replacing the solutions, this equation is for practical purposes an
 ODE.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, we obtain a liquidity premium for the capital share in wealth:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[r_{t}^{k}-r_{t}^{m}\right]=\left(1-\gamma\right)\left(R_{t}^{i}\left(1-(1-\phi_{t})\omega^{k}\right)+1\right)^{-\gamma}\left(1-\phi_{t}\right)R_{t}^{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Specializing to the log case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the log case, the first-order condition is taken after the limit to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 is taken.
 Therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[r_{t}^{k}-r_{t}^{m}\right]=\frac{1-\phi_{t}}{R_{t}^{i}\left(1-(1-\phi_{t})\omega^{k}\right)+1}R_{t}^{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression is a liquidity premium.
 The idea is that money is dominated in return, but has an additional value
 as collateral, captured by the term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left(1-\gamma\right)}{\left(R_{t}^{i}\left(1-(1-\phi_{t})\omega^{k}\right)+1\right)^{^{-\gamma}}}\left(\left(1-\phi_{t}\right)R_{t}^{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset

or in the log case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[r_{t}^{k}-r_{t}^{m}\right]=\frac{\left(1-\phi_{t}\right)R_{t}^{i}}{R_{t}^{i}\left(1-(1-\phi_{t})\omega^{k}\right)+1}.\label{eq:portfolio.cond}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The numerator captures the advantages in terms of levered returns.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 captures the levered return on your investment, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-\phi_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 the collateral value of money.
 The denominator captures the relative jump in marginal utilities when money
 increases.
 
\end_layout

